y get more useful. There are only a few industries that haven=E2=80=99t beh=
aved like that: finance, maybe healthcare.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The reason, he believes, is that products have been so undifferentiated, so=
 it became a game of customer acquisition and segmentation. There was a per=
iod a few years ago where there was a startup focused on practically every =
demographic cross-section you could imagine.=C2=A0
Ramp has been working to change that, as a financial technology company foc=
used on helping its customers spend less. It=E2=80=99s been successful so f=
ar, building products that customers love to do things they didn=E2=80=99t =
realize a financial services company could do.=C2=A0
AI, done right, accelerates that.=C2=A0
A finance platform that gets more differentiated with scale =E2=80=93 that =
saves customers more time and money as it grows by virtue of better data, p=
roducts, integrations, and that can proactively do smarter and smarter thin=
gs on its customers behalf to make their businesses more profitable =E2=80=
=93 might be the most valuable platform there is to own.=C2=A0
Now is the time for someone to build that platform. Will it be Ramp?=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s certainly not guaranteed.=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s a world in which AGI comes and gets so good at everything t=
hat companies hire OpenAI to do everything they need to do, from finance to=
 engineering to HR. If you=E2=80=99re going to bet on AI leading to consoli=
dation, you have to consider the risk that it really consolidates.=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s also a world, a more likely one, in which AI agents can ope=
rate among many best-in-class point solutions in a way that feels no differ=
ent to the user than using one solution. This world might actually weaken s=
ome of Ramp=E2=80=99s advantages. BILL=E2=80=99s interface is rough for a h=
uman, but it does offer both Accounts Payable and Accounts Receivable, wher=
eas Ramp doesn=E2=80=99t offer AR yet. In this world, the work building del=
ightful software for customers may end up being less important than buildin=
g feature-rich point solutions that robots can figure out.=C2=A0
Then there are the millions of more mundane reasons it might not work, or t=
hat it might not get quite as big as I imagine with my optimist=E2=80=99s h=
at on. If it=E2=80=99s no longer able to attract and retain the most talent=
ed employees, that will be an issue. If its AI agents abuse their power to =
make decisions that are in the best interest of Ramp but not the customer, =
that=E2=80=99s a huge issue.
Doing big, complex, multi-product things, and stringing all of those things=
 together in a cohesive way, is just hard.=C2=A0
But the more interesting scenario to imagine is the one in which Ramp reall=
y can help make companies more profitable at scale.
That would mean that companies can spend more of their time and money on th=
e things that matter to grow their businesses.=C2=A0
Employees can spend more time doing what they love to do at work=E2=80=A6 o=
r even get more done in less time working.=C2=A0 That=E2=80=99s one of AI=
=E2=80=99s more exciting promises: not that we won=E2=80=99t have to work a=
nymore, but that we can each do more with less.=C2=A0
I think we=E2=80=99re a long way away from AI replacing everything humans d=
o, but it can certainly replace the most machine-like work we do. Filing ex=
pense reports, booking travel, negotiating for discounts on software produc=
ts (with limited information), closing the books at month-end =E2=80=93 the=
se are all things that we should just hire software to do for us.=C2=A0
The history of automation isn=E2=80=99t that certain people lose their jobs=
 forever while others continue to grind. It=E2=80=99s the history of more p=
eople spending less time to produce more output. We have weekends now, and =
vacation. Kids start working later in life, they can go to college. And adu=
lts retire earlier, instead of having to work until they die.=C2=A0
I love working. Even if I got the fattest UBI check, I would continue to re=
ad, write, talk to smart people, and invest. But there=E2=80=99s plenty of =
stuff I don=E2=80=99t like about working. If AI can eliminate all of that s=
o I can focus on what I love, bring it on.=C2=A0
As more people spend more time on the things they love doing at work =E2=80=
=93 building things, spending time with customers, focusing for hours (or d=
ays) on really hard problems =E2=80=93 they=E2=80=99ll be more productive, =
and generate more value.=C2=A0
As companies stop wasting money on software seats they don=E2=80=99t use an=
d travel booking fees they don=E2=80=99t need to pay, they can hire more of=
 these more productive people to do the very human things that add value.=
=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s an anti-Private Equity way of making a business more profitabl=
e: making each employee happier and more productive such that companies can=
 hire more of them to add more value. Jevons Paradox [ https://substack.com=
/redirect/b4c8410f-6aa4-411b-bbbb-94c46b72e9fd?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5=
T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] is a hell of a drug.=C2=A0
Plus, more talented people might start their own companies if they just nee=
d to be really good at the thing that they=E2=80=99re good, and not also go=
od at all the undifferentiated work that comes with keeping a company runni=
ng.=C2=A0
More value might flow to the companies that care about crafting great produ=
cts and delivering great value when agents with tons of data help make purc=
hasing decisions.
There are tons of second and third order effects in the world in which Ramp=
 succeeds in making companies more profitable, not the least of which is th=
at profits can be reinvested in growth, and growth is good.=C2=A0=C2=A0
And what=E2=80=99s a business that quite literally makes every other busine=
ss more profitable worth?=C2=A0
Man, I don=E2=80=99t know. A lot.
Thanks to Eric, Karim, Calvin, William, Jo, Lindsay, Lulu, and the Ramp tea=
m for input and feedback on this piece!
That=E2=80=99s all for today. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox with a We=
ekly Dose on Friday.
Thanks for reading,
Packy

