font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">But this is just t=
he beginning of what Ramp Travel can become as the company builds more AI-p=
owered features into the product.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 5=
5); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Once you book,=
 for example, it could scan for better prices on the same flight or hotel a=
nd rebook for you, automatically saving you money with no extra time.&#160;=
</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px;=
 margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Because Ramp will see so many trips across its more t=
han 25,000 corporate customers, it will be able to suggest expense controls=
 based on what other travelers are paying, not a generic &#8220;average cos=
t for this route.&#8221; It might also suggest restaurants, hotels, and oth=
er local trips that other Ramp companies enjoyed.</p><p style=3D"color: rgb=
(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><spa=
n>Eventually, </span><em>you</em><span> won&#8217;t need to book at all.&#1=
60;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-hei=
ght: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Since Ramp knows every employee&#8217;s tra=
vel policies and spending limits, and because it sees where all of its cust=
omers book in certain cities, booking travel with Ramp will eventually be a=
s easy as sending a text: &#8220;I need to go to the Marketing Offsite in M=
iami in March.&#8221;&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-siz=
e: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Everything else will happe=
n automatically, other than the fun part: actually traveling.&#160;</p><p s=
tyle=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin:=
 0 0 20px 0;">The easier it makes the process, the more spend customers wil=
l manage through Ramp. The more customers spend through Ramp, the smarter R=
amp will get and the better deals Ramp will be able to negotiate for its cu=
stomers. AI can help make Ramp easier and smarter, and save customers time =
and money. It&#8217;s an incentive-aligned flywheel.&#160;</p><p style=3D"c=
olor: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px=
 0;">Beyond Travel, the more parts of a company Ramp touches, the more valu=
e it can provide as it orchestrates workflows that previously existed acros=
s multiple disparate platforms.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55)=
; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>All of thi=
s compounds. As more companies use Ramp for more things, Ramp is able to sa=
ve customers more time and more money. That may be why Ramp investor </span=
><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/177d1c86-ecf0-4694-ba2b-d934aecef=
230?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=
 style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">Keith Rabois=
 told Harry Stebbings</a><span>, &#8220;I think all CFOs of the future will=
 want to run on Ramp and they'll be reckless if they don't.&#8221;</span></=
p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; m=
argin: 0 0 20px 0;">This is one of the ways learning about Ramp Travel shap=
ed my views on the AI opportunity, which is where we&#8217;ll turn now. Sta=
rting with the idea that AI will lead to extreme consolidation.&#160;</p><p=
 style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margi=
n: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>AI Will Drive Extreme Consolidation</strong></p><p =
style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin=
: 0 0 20px 0;">Software isn&#8217;t dead, but a lot of today&#8217;s B2B so=
ftware companies will die.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); fon=
t-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Integrated platforms =
that own customer workflows will pull more of a buyer&#8217;s jobs to be do=
ne into what they do, and enjoy accumulating advantages that turn previousl=
y competitive markets into winner-take-most markets.&#160;</p><p style=3D"c=
olor: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px=
 0;"><span>These winning platforms will be more valuable than today&#8217;s=
 biggest platforms, and the small handful of winners may be more valuable t=
han </span><em>all </em><span>software companies today. It&#8217;s a power =
law.</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-he=
ight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>In other words, </span><strong>AI wi=
ll drive extreme consolidation</strong><span>.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"=
color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20p=
x 0;"><span>There&#8217;s one idea that SaaS companies are at risk because =
anyone will be able to make great software. I think the more likely outcome=
 in B2B will be that </span><strong>point solutions</strong><span> &#8211; =
software products that do one thing &#8211; are more at risk from integrate=
d platforms that can more easily bundle point solutions into their platform=
, making their whole offering more valuable as they do.&#160;</span></p><p =
style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin=
: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>This has already been happening pre-AI, as highlighted=
 by Ramp&#8217;s ability to successfully build Expensify and Bill competito=
rs into its product offering. The </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/re=
direct/fdcfa601-8105-4676-8e39-6b323b8b117d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7G=
nA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); t=
ext-decoration: underline;">Compound Startup</a><span>, popularized by Ripp=
ling CEO Parker Conrad, is in.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 5=
5, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">&#8220;Gen=
tlemen, there are only two ways I know of to make money,&#8221; Jim Barksda=
le said. &#8220;Bundling and unbundling.&#8221; We are already in a bundlin=
g phase. It will happen faster and more violently now.&#160;</p><p style=3D=
"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20=
px 0;"><strong>Customers want to buy from as few companies as possible to s=
olve their Job to Be Done</strong><span>.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color=
: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"=
>In a recent series of conversations with Ramp customers, Sands Capital fou=
nd that &#8220;there was a loud and clear desire (1) to consolidate even mo=
re parts of the finance stack and (2) for Ramp to be that consolidation par=
tner.&#8221;&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; =
line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">It makes sense. Using one platform =
is simply easier for people than using multiple.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color=
: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"=
>Somewhat counterintuitively, the more choices buyers have &#8212; the more=
 companies or individuals spin up point solutions &#8211; the more they&#82=
17;ll want to retreat to one product they trust.</p><div class=3D"captioned=
