<p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; mar=
gin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>As long as Ramp is at feature parity on each of the=
 point solutions it&#8217;s replacing, using Ramp a no-brainer. And </span>=
<strong>getting to feature parity becomes easier with AI</strong><span>.&#1=
60;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-hei=
ght: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Plus, bundling software likely means saving=
 money (and time) versus buying a number of separate point solutions. Micro=
soft is the most valuable company in the world at $3 trillion in large part=
 because of these dynamics.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); fo=
nt-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>As a platfor=
m adds more products and data, each product gets more valuable</strong><spa=
n>.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; li=
ne-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">By combining credit cards and expense=
 management, for example, Ramp is able to automatically match receipts to t=
ransactions in a way that Expensify can&#8217;t without the credit card.&#1=
60;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26=
px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">With more products and more integrations, Ramp get=
s more data about a company, which it can leverage in multiple different wa=
ys.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-heig=
ht: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">As one example, because it integrates with O=
kta, it understands which employees are using which products. Because compa=
nies pay for those products with Ramp cards and Bill Pay, it understands ho=
w many seats companies are paying for.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, =
55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Today, th=
at means that Ramp alerts customers when they&#8217;re paying for unused se=
ats, which saves them money. With AI, Ramp may be able to use that data and=
 those integrations to proactively manage its customers&#8217; vendors to s=
ave them money and time, automatically, like an employee would today.&#160;=
</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px;=
 margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Eric told me that </span><strong>as Ramp has ad=
ded more products, it&#8217;s winning more customers, selling more products=
 to each, and improving product monetization, which has led to improved con=
tribution profits.</strong><span>&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54=
, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">New coh=
orts are adopting new products at an accelerating rate &#8211; one-third of=
 new customers in Q1 2024 have already adopted Bill Pay &#8211; and older c=
ohorts are expanding as they adopt more Ramp products. It all compounds.&#1=
60;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26=
px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">&#8220;Great platforms do this,&#8221; he said. &#=
8220;With each new product, it should all get easier. I think this is when =
companies go from good to great.&#8221;&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54,=
 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">This wil=
l continue to accelerate. When I asked Logan Bartlett for his thoughts on R=
amp&#8217;s opportunity in AI, he told me:&#160;</p><blockquote style=3D"bo=
rder-left: 4px solid #51b4e9; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><p style=3D"colo=
r: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;=
 margin-left: 20px;"><em><span>I kind of think if you run a company and are=
 not using Ramp by now, you are either insane or just lazy (or both?). Ever=
y product they put out is exceptional and it&#8217;s clear at this point th=
at the gap between what they&#8217;re doing and what everyone else is doing=
 is only increasing. </span><strong>AI is a new paradigm that will only com=
pound that.</strong><span>&#160;</span></em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"co=
lor: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px =
0;">Imagine two products with the same software. Product A is built on top =
of less data. Product B is built on top of more data. Which is more valuabl=
e?&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-heigh=
t: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>As software becomes easier to build, th=
e advantage shifts even more heavily in favor of the companies with the bes=
t data. And as software begins to use that data to do </span><strong>work o=
n its customers&#8217; behalf</strong><span>, that advantage gets even more=
 pronounced.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size:=
 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>AI will flip product=
s from passive to active</strong><span>, and like employees, products can d=
o better work if they have better information.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"=
color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20p=
x 0;">Take something like accounting. AI is really good at looking at a gen=
eral ledger, understanding how things have been done in the past, and organ=
izing new transactions into the right place. It&#8217;s not hard to imagine=
 that with the right data, Ramp&#8217;s AI might get a company&#8217;s mont=
hly close to the point where the CFO just needs to review and sign off.&#16=
0;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26p=
x; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>At a certain point, if you </span><em>really =
</em><span>want to be &#8220;just lazy,&#8221; that&#8217;s even more of a =
reason to be on Ramp.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); f=
ont-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>If a platfo=
rm can do more work for its customer with more data, there&#8217;s an incen=
tive for customers to move even more of what they do into a smaller number =
of platforms.</strong><span>&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55,=
 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>As a r=
esult, platforms that own specific workflows can both win more of their exi=
sting categories </span><em>and</em><span> eat more adjacent categories tha=
t can be integrated into those workflows.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color=
: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"=
>But not every company that owns a workflow today will benefit equally.&#16=
0;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26p=
x; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>Who Takes Advantage of Owning the Workflow?=
</strong></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-heig=
ht: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>People seem to be converging on this i=
dea that one of the things that one set of winners will be the incumbents w=
ho </span><strong>own customers&#8217; workflows. &#8220;</strong><span>Own=
ing the workflow&#8221; means embedding the product so deeply into the cust=
omer's operations that it's not just a tool, it&#8217;s the nervous system =
of a department.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-s=
ize: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">This is a consensus take=
 at this point, and I&#8217;m guilty of it, too.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color=
: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"=
><span>In </span><em><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/1d077f3a-935a=
