rnly fragmented in the face of technology. &#8220;It&#8217;s weird,&#8221; =
he said, &#8220;As Amazon gets bigger, as Microsoft gets bigger, and as Met=
a gets bigger, they get more useful. There are only a few industries that h=
aven&#8217;t behaved like that: finance, maybe healthcare.&#8221;&#160;</p>=
<p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; mar=
gin: 0 0 20px 0;">The reason, he believes, is that products have been so un=
differentiated, so it became a game of customer acquisition and segmentatio=
n. There was a period a few years ago where there was a startup focused on =
practically every demographic cross-section you could imagine.&#160;</p><p =
style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin=
: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Ramp has been working to change that, as a financial t=
echnology company focused on helping its customers spend </span><em>less</e=
m><span>. It&#8217;s been successful so far, building products that custome=
rs love to do things they didn&#8217;t realize a financial services company=
 could do.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 1=
6px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">AI, done right, accelerates th=
at.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-heig=
ht: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">A finance platform that gets more differenti=
ated with scale &#8211; that saves customers more time and money as it grow=
s by virtue of better data, products, integrations, and that can proactivel=
y do smarter and smarter things on its customers behalf to make their busin=
esses more profitable &#8211; might be the most valuable platform there is =
to own.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-=
height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Now is the time for </span><em>som=
eone</em><span> to build that platform. Will it be Ramp?&#160;</span></p><p=
 style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margi=
n: 0 0 20px 0;">It&#8217;s certainly not guaranteed.&#160;</p><p style=3D"c=
olor: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px=
 0;"><span>There&#8217;s a world in which AGI comes and gets so good at </s=
pan><em>everything</em><span> that companies hire OpenAI to do everything t=
hey need to do, from finance to engineering to HR. If you&#8217;re going to=
 bet on AI leading to consolidation, you have to consider the risk that it =
</span><em>really </em><span>consolidates.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"colo=
r: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;=
">There&#8217;s also a world, a more likely one, in which AI agents can ope=
rate among many best-in-class point solutions in a way that feels no differ=
ent to the user than using one solution. This world might actually weaken s=
ome of Ramp&#8217;s advantages. BILL&#8217;s interface is rough for a human=
, but it does offer both Accounts Payable and Accounts Receivable, whereas =
Ramp doesn&#8217;t offer AR yet. In this world, the work building delightfu=
l software for customers may end up being less important than building feat=
ure-rich point solutions that robots can figure out.&#160;</p><p style=3D"c=
olor: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px=
 0;"><span>Then there are the millions of more mundane reasons it might not=
 work, or that it might not get </span><em>quite</em><span> as big as I ima=
gine with my optimist&#8217;s hat on. If it&#8217;s no longer able to attra=
ct and retain the most talented employees, that will be an issue. If its AI=
 agents abuse their power to make decisions that are in the best interest o=
f Ramp but not the customer, that&#8217;s a huge issue.</span></p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">Doing big, complex, multi-product things, and stringing all of th=
ose things together in a cohesive way, is just hard.&#160;</p><p style=3D"c=
olor: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px=
 0;"><strong>But the more interesting scenario to imagine is the one in whi=
ch Ramp really can help make companies more profitable at scale.</strong></=
p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; m=
argin: 0 0 20px 0;">That would mean that companies can spend more of their =
time and money on the things that matter to grow their businesses.&#160;</p=
><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; ma=
rgin: 0 0 20px 0;">Employees can spend more time doing what they love to do=
 at work&#8230; or even get more done in less time working.&#160; That&#821=
7;s one of AI&#8217;s more exciting promises: not that we won&#8217;t have =
to work anymore, but that we can each do more with less.&#160;</p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">I think we&#8217;re a long way away from AI replacing everything =
humans do, but it can certainly replace the most machine-like work we do. F=
iling expense reports, booking travel, negotiating for discounts on softwar=
e products (with limited information), closing the books at month-end &#821=
1; these are all things that we should just hire software to do for us.&#16=
0;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26p=
x; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The history of automation isn&#8217;t that certain =
people lose their jobs forever while others continue to grind. It&#8217;s t=
he history of more people spending less time to produce more output. We hav=
e weekends now, and vacation. Kids start working later in life, they can go=
 to college. And adults retire earlier, instead of having to work until the=
y die.&#160;</p><div class=3D"captioned-image-container-static" style=3D"fo=
nt-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 32px auto;"><figure style=3D"marg=
